    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Tourists in Venice</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Tim Jarrell, Fodor's Travel Publications, says majority of Americans who travel abroad behave respectfully (June 10 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''To Venetians' Sorrow, the Sightseers Come in Battalions'' (Venice Journal, June 10) evokes a belittling image of travelers as an ''ugly Fodor's-toting horde.'' While Venice's problems are serious, they aren't rooted in the misbehavior of tourists (with or without Fodor's guides); some Venetians, frustrated with the overcrowding, have resorted to stereotyping tourists.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''To Venetians' Sorrow, the Sightseers Come in Battalions'' (Venice Journal, June 10) evokes a belittling image of travelers as an ''ugly Fodor's-toting horde.'' While Venice's problems are serious, they aren't rooted in the misbehavior of tourists (with or without Fodor's guides); some Venetians, frustrated with the overcrowding, have resorted to stereotyping tourists.</p>
        <p>It's important for Americans to discover the world beyond our borders; the majority of those who do so behave respectfully when abroad.</p>
        <p>TIM JARRELL  Publisher  Fodor's Travel Publications  New York, June 14, 2004</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
